<p class="article-lead">A perfume filling service converts bulk liquid and packaging components into saleable units. Buyers supplying their own formula or materials need much more than a price per fill: the factory needs compatible components, traceable materials and clear release criteria.</p>
<h2>Information needed before a line trial</h2><p>Provide bottle and neck drawings, pump specification, target fill, liquid information, component quantities and finished-pack assembly instructions. State whether the service includes crimping or torque, collar and cap fitting, coding, labeling, boxing, cellophane and export cartons.</p>
<h2>Allow for yield and rejects</h2><p>Supplied quantities should include an agreed allowance for setup, testing, cosmetic defects and damage. Define who pays when a customer-supplied pump does not fit or a bottle tolerance causes leakage. A small trial can reveal issues before the full shipment reaches the line.</p>
<h2>Release the batch against a specification</h2><p>Agree fill tolerance, spray check, closure check, appearance standard, coding position and packing count. Keep material lot references and finished batch records. Without these, a filling service may complete the physical work but leave the buyer unable to investigate a later complaint.</p>
